          "text": "According to the Algorithms and Data Structures section of your documentation, every developer should know these essentials:\n            **Core Data Structures:**\n\n            1. **Arrays & Linked Lists**\n              - Arrays: Fast indexed access, good for ordered collections\n              - Linked Lists: Efficient insertion/deletion at nodes\n\n            2. **Stacks & Queues**\n              - Stack (LIFO): undo/redo, call stack, DFS\n              - Queue (FIFO): task scheduling, BFS\n              - Priority Queue: items processed by priority\n\n            3. **Trees**\n              - Binary Search Trees for ordered data\n              - Traversals: inOrder, preOrder, postOrder, levelOrder\n\n            4. **Hash Tables**\n              - Fast key-value lookup\n              - Important for caching and dictionaries\n\n            5. **Graphs**\n              - Model relationships and networks\n              - DFS, BFS, Dijkstra's shortest path\n\n            **Essential Algorithms:**\n\n            1. **Sorting**\n              - Quick Sort\n              - Merge Sort\n              - Heap Sort\n\n            2. **Searching**\n              - Binary Search\n              - Finding first/last occurrence in sorted arrays\n\n            3. **Dynamic Programming**\n              - Fibonacci\n              - Longest Common Subsequence\n              - Knapsack Problem\n              - Coin Change\n              - Edit Distance\n\n            **Most Important Concepts:**\n            - Time complexity (Big O)\n            - Space complexity\n            - Trade-offs between structures\n            - When to use each based on access patterns\n\n            These form the foundation for problem-solving and system design."
